        {
          kind: 'commentary',
          id: 'heb12-sion-contrast',
          html:
            'Instead of fire and darkness, you have come to the city of the living God. Instead of terror, a feast. Instead of an isolated people listening from a distance, an <em>innumerable company</em>—angels, the church of the firstborn, the spirits of just people already made perfect. You are not alone. You are not afraid. You are home.',
        },
        {
          kind: 'christ',
          id: 'heb12-christ-mediator',
          title: 'Christ Connection — The Mediator and the Better Blood',
          html:
            'Jesus is the mediator of the new covenant (Heb. 8:6). The old covenant was a contract written on stone that Israel could not keep. The new covenant is written on the heart. And Jesus, through His blood, has made it unbreakable. Abel&apos;s blood cried out for justice (Gen. 4:10). Jesus&apos; blood cries out for mercy. Where the first death asked &ldquo;Why?&rdquo;, Jesus&apos; death says &ldquo;Forgiven.&rdquo; His blood speaks better things than Abel&apos;s ever could.',
        },
        {
          kind: 'commentary',
          id: 'heb12-mediator-intro',
          html:
            'A mediator is someone who stands between two parties and brings them together. Jesus stands between you and the Father. He has made it possible for you to approach God, not through fear, but through grace.',
        },
        {
          kind: 'commentary',
          id: 'heb12-abel-intro',
          html:
            'Abel&apos;s blood was the first innocent blood shed, crying out for justice (Gen. 4:10). Jesus&apos; blood is the final innocent blood shed, speaking forgiveness over all who believe. The contrast is not accidental. One death demands payment. The other offers it.',
        },
        {
          kind: 'carry',
          html:
            'You have been invited to a table, not a courtroom. You have been called into a family, not a contract. The God you are approaching is your judge, but He is also your Father. The barrier between you and Him is not fear—it is sin. And even that has been paid for. You can draw near. You are invited all the way in.',
